SUMMARY:Spring 2026 Colloquium Series with Eduardo Herrera
DESCRIPTION:The Center for Latin American and Caribbean Studies is proud 
 to present the continuation of its Colloquium Series for Spring 2026.  We
  welcome Dr. Eduardo Herrera&#160\;as he presents Argentina's Soccer Chan
 ting Tradition\, from Neighborhood Stadiums to Global Stages.Abstract:&#1
 60\;  At the 2022 FIFA World Cup in Qatar\, Argentine fans adopted "Mucha
 chos\," adapted from a song by La Mosca Tse Tse\, as an unofficial anthem
 . As Argentina advanced under Lionel Messi and ultimately won the tournam
 ent\, the song drew global attention for its role in animating collective
  fandom. Yet such national-team chanting is exceptional\, since these squ
 ads convene only intermittently. The sustained intensity of Argentine soc
 cer chanting is rooted instead in local club culture\, where weekly match
 es enable ritualized gatherings and the accumulation of shared repertoire
 s. Chanting traditions date to the 1910s\, when carnival murga music info
 rmed early participatory singing. In the 1940s and 1950s\, fans expanded 
 melodic borrowing and lyrical complexity. From the 1970s onward\, chants 
 became more confrontational\, a shift that coincided with the 1976–1983
  military dictatorship. By the 1990s\, clubs maintained extensive reperto
 ires\, drawing on diverse popular genres. The late twentieth century saw 
 global television networks amplify Argentina's influence\, establishing i
 t as a major exporter of chants. In the twenty-first century\, digital pl
 atforms such as YouTube and WhatsApp have accelerated their transnational
  circulation.  This presentation traces Argentina's emergence as a global
  hub for soccer chanting\, emphasizing its cultural history\, expressive 
 force\, and role in shaping collective identity at the intersection of sp
 ort\, music\, and globalization.  &#160\;Eduardo Herrera is an associate 
 professor in the department of Folklore and Ethnomusicology and the direc
 tor of the Ethnomusicology Institute at Indiana University Bloomington. W
 ith a PhD from University of Illinois Urbana-Champaign\, His research com
 prises topics from sound studies to Latinx cultural practices and colonia
 lity/postcoloniality/decoloniality.  The CLACS Spring 2026 Colloquium mee
 ts Mondays from February through April\, with faculty and guest speakers 
 engaging Latin America and the Caribbean through research on history\, cu
 lture\, language\, politics\, and the arts. Check the CLACS Calendar (htt
 ps://events.iu.edu/clacs/) for details.
X-ALT-DESC;FMTTYPE=text/html:<p>  The Center for Latin American and Carib
 bean Studies is proud to present the continuation of its <strong>Colloqui
 um Series for Spring 2026</strong>.</p><p>  We welcome <strong>Dr. Eduard
 o Herrera</strong>&#160\;as he presents <strong><em>Argentina's Soccer Ch
 anting Tradition\, from Neighborhood Stadiums to Global Stages.</em></str
 ong></p><p><strong>Abstract:&#160\;</strong></p><div data-olk-copy-source
 ="MessageBody">  At the 2022 FIFA World Cup in Qatar\, Argentine fans ado
 pted "Muchachos\," adapted from a song by La Mosca Tse Tse\, as an unoffi
 cial anthem. As Argentina advanced under Lionel Messi and ultimately won 
 the tournament\, the song drew global attention for its role in animating
  collective fandom. Yet such national-team chanting is exceptional\, sinc
 e these squads convene only intermittently. The sustained intensity of Ar
 gentine soccer chanting is rooted instead in local club culture\, where w
 eekly matches enable ritualized gatherings and the accumulation of shared
  repertoires. Chanting traditions date to the 1910s\, when carnival murga
  music informed early participatory singing. In the 1940s and 1950s\, fan
 s expanded melodic borrowing and lyrical complexity. From the 1970s onwar
 d\, chants became more confrontational\, a shift that coincided with the 
 1976–1983 military dictatorship. By the 1990s\, clubs maintained extens
 ive repertoires\, drawing on diverse popular genres. The late twentieth c
 entury saw global television networks amplify Argentina's influence\, est
 ablishing it as a major exporter of chants. In the twenty-first century\,
  digital platforms such as YouTube and WhatsApp have accelerated their tr
 ansnational circulation.</div><div>  This presentation traces Argentina's
  emergence as a global hub for soccer chanting\, emphasizing its cultural
  history\, expressive force\, and role in shaping collective identity at 
 the intersection of sport\, music\, and globalization.</div><p>  &#160\;<
 /p><p><strong>Eduardo Herrera</strong> is an associate professor in the d
 epartment of Folklore and Ethnomusicology and the director of the Ethnomu
 sicology Institute at Indiana University Bloomington. With a PhD from Uni
 versity of Illinois Urbana-Champaign\, His research comprises topics from
  sound studies to Latinx cultural practices and coloniality/postcoloniali
 ty/decoloniality.</p><p>  The CLACS Spring 2026 Colloquium meets Mondays 
 from February through April\, with faculty and guest speakers engaging La
 tin America and the Caribbean through research on history\, culture\, lan
 guage\, politics\, and the arts. Check the <a href="https://events.iu.edu
 /clacs/">CLACS Calendar</a> for details.</p><p><picture class="lw_image l
